# Sprint 4: Live Mirror-Canvas

**Duration:** 2 weeks  
**Sprint Goal:** Implement bidirectional synchronization between visual timeline and code editor using CRDT technology  
**Success Criteria:** Real-time collaborative editing works flawlessly with visual-code synchronization

---

## Sprint Objectives

1. **CRDT Integration**: Implement Y.js for conflict-free collaborative editing
2. **Bidirectional Binding**: Connect visual timeline changes to code updates and vice versa
3. **Real-time Collaboration**: Enable multiple users to edit experiments simultaneously
4. **Conflict Resolution**: Handle merge conflicts gracefully with user control
5. **Performance Optimization**: Maintain 60fps interactions during live collaboration

---

## Sprint Backlog

### Epic: CRDT State Management
**Story Points: 8**

#### GUI-005: Integrate Automerge State Store
**Points: 5 | Priority: Critical**

**Description:** Implement Y.js CRDT as the canonical state management solution for experiment data.

**Technical Requirements:**
- Y.js document structure for experiment representation
- WebRTC peer-to-peer connections for low-latency sync
- WebSocket fallback for NAT traversal issues
- Offline-first design with eventual consistency

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Y.js document correctly represents ForgeScript AST
- [ ] Real-time synchronization between multiple clients
- [ ] Offline editing with automatic merge on reconnection
- [ ] Conflict resolution preserves user intent
- [ ] Performance maintains <100ms sync latency

**CRDT Implementation:**
```typescript
// @psyforge/collaboration
import * as Y from 'yjs';
import { WebrtcProvider } from 'y-webrtc';
import { WebsocketProvider } from 'y-websocket';

export class ExperimentCRDT {
  private doc: Y.Doc;
  private experimentMap: Y.Map<any>;
  private providers: Array<WebrtcProvider | WebsocketProvider>;

  constructor(experimentId: string) {
    this.doc = new Y.Doc();
    this.experimentMap = this.doc.getMap('experiment');

    // Dual connectivity for reliability
    this.providers = [
      new WebrtcProvider(experimentId, this.doc),
      new WebsocketProvider('wss://sync.psyforge.org', experimentId, this.doc)
    ];
  }

  // Subscribe to experiment changes
  onExperimentChange(callback: (changes: ExperimentChanges) => void): () => void;

  // Apply changes from visual editor
  updateFromVisual(path: string[], value: any): void;

  // Apply changes from code editor
  updateFromCode(ast: ForgeScriptAST): void;

  // Get current experiment state
  getCurrentExperiment(): CompiledExperiment;
}
```

#### GUI-019: CRDT Performance Optimization
**Points: 3 | Priority: High**

**Description:** Optimize CRDT operations for large experiments and frequent updates.

**Technical Requirements:**
- Efficient delta compression for minimal network traffic
- Selective synchronization for large experiment trees
- Memory usage optimization for long editing sessions
- Batched updates to reduce operation overhead

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Sub-100ms sync latency for typical changes
- [ ] Memory usage stable during extended sessions
- [ ] Network traffic minimized through delta compression
- [ ] Large experiments (1000+ trials) sync efficiently
- [ ] Batched operations reduce CPU overhead

---

### Epic: Visual-Code Bidirectional Binding
**Story Points: 9**

#### GUI-006: Visual-to-AST Binding
**Points: 5 | Priority: Critical**

**Description:** Implement automatic code generation when users modify the visual timeline.

**Technical Requirements:**
- Real-time AST updates from visual timeline changes
- Preserve user code formatting and comments where possible
- Handle complex operations like trial reordering and duplication
- Maintain undo/redo stack consistency

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Drag-and-drop timeline changes update code immediately
- [ ] Trial reordering preserves trial content and metadata
- [ ] Timeline modifications generate valid ForgeScript code
- [ ] Undo/redo works across visual and code changes
- [ ] Code formatting preserved during automatic updates

**Visual-to-Code Binding:**
```typescript
// @psyforge/binding
export class VisualCodeBinding {
  private crdt: ExperimentCRDT;
  private codeEditor: monaco.editor.IStandaloneCodeEditor;
  private visualTimeline: TimelineCanvas;

  constructor(crdt: ExperimentCRDT, editor: monaco.editor.IStandaloneCodeEditor, timeline: TimelineCanvas) {
    this.crdt = crdt;
    this.codeEditor = editor;
    this.visualTimeline = timeline;

    this.setupVisualToCodeBinding();
    this.setupCodeToVisualBinding();
  }

  private setupVisualToCodeBinding(): void {
    // Listen for visual timeline changes
    this.visualTimeline.on('elementMoved', (event) => {
      this.updateASTFromVisual(event);
      this.regenerateCode();
    });

    this.visualTimeline.on('elementAdded', (event) => {
      this.addElementToAST(event);
      this.insertCodeAtPosition(event.position);
    });
  }

  private updateASTFromVisual(event: VisualChangeEvent): void {
    // Convert visual changes to AST operations
    // Update CRDT with new structure
    // Trigger code regeneration
  }

  private regenerateCode(): void {
    // Generate ForgeScript code from current AST
    // Preserve user formatting where possible
    // Update Monaco editor content
  }
}
```

#### GUI-007: AST-to-Code Binding
**Points: 4 | Priority: Critical**

**Description:** Update visual timeline when users edit ForgeScript code.

**Technical Requirements:**
- Incremental parsing for real-time code-to-visual updates
- Error handling for invalid code states
- Visual highlighting of syntax errors
- Smooth animations for timeline updates

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Code changes update visual timeline in real-time
- [ ] Syntax errors highlighted in both code and visual panes
- [ ] Invalid code states don't break visual representation
- [ ] Timeline animations provide smooth feedback
- [ ] Incremental parsing maintains editor performance

---

### Epic: Real-time Collaboration Features
**Story Points: 6**

#### GUI-020: Multi-User Presence & Awareness
**Points: 3 | Priority: High**

**Description:** Show user presence and real-time editing awareness in both visual and code views.

**Technical Requirements:**
- User cursors and selections in code editor
- Visual indicators for users editing timeline elements
- User identification with avatars and colors
- Awareness of user focus and activity

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Multiple user cursors visible in code editor
- [ ] Visual timeline shows which user is editing each element
- [ ] User identification clear with consistent colors
- [ ] Inactive users fade out after timeout
- [ ] Smooth presence updates without performance impact

**Collaboration Awareness:**
```typescript
// User presence in visual timeline
export interface UserPresence {
  userId: string;
  userName: string;
  color: string;
  cursor?: {
    line: number;
    column: number;
  };
  selection?: {
    elementId: string;
    elementType: 'timeline' | 'trial' | 'stimulus';
  };
  lastActivity: number;
}

// Visual presence indicators
export class PresenceIndicators {
  showUserCursor(presence: UserPresence): void;
  showElementSelection(presence: UserPresence): void;
  updateUserActivity(userId: string): void;
  removeInactiveUsers(): void;
}
```

#### GUI-021: Conflict Resolution UI
**Points: 3 | Priority: Medium**

**Description:** Provide user interface for resolving merge conflicts when they occur.

**Technical Requirements:**
- Visual diff view for conflicting changes
- Three-way merge interface (base, theirs, yours)
- Automatic resolution suggestions
- Manual conflict resolution controls

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Conflicts detected and surfaced immediately
- [ ] Clear visual representation of conflicting changes
- [ ] Users can choose resolution strategy
- [ ] Automatic resolution works for simple conflicts
- [ ] Manual resolution maintains experiment validity

---

### Epic: Performance & Reliability
**Story Points: 4**

#### INF-005b: Instrument Studio with Telemetry Hooks
**Points: 2 | Priority: Medium**

**Description:** Add comprehensive telemetry for monitoring collaboration performance and reliability.

**Technical Requirements:**
- CRDT sync latency monitoring
- Visual-code binding performance tracking
- Collaboration session metrics
- Error rate monitoring and alerting

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Sync latency tracked and reported
- [ ] Binding performance monitored in real-time
- [ ] Collaboration session quality metrics
- [ ] Automatic alerts for performance degradation
- [ ] Privacy-compliant telemetry collection

#### GUI-022: Offline Mode & Sync Recovery
**Points: 2 | Priority: Medium**

**Description:** Handle network disconnections gracefully with offline editing and automatic recovery.

**Technical Requirements:**
- Local state persistence during offline periods
- Automatic reconnection and sync on network restore
- Conflict resolution for offline changes
- User notifications for connection status

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Editing continues seamlessly when offline
- [ ] Network reconnection triggers automatic sync
- [ ] Offline changes merge correctly on reconnection
- [ ] Connection status clearly indicated to users
- [ ] No data loss during network interruptions

---

## Definition of Done

**For each ticket:**
- [ ] Implementation with comprehensive unit tests (>90% coverage)
- [ ] Real-time collaboration tested with multiple concurrent users
- [ ] Performance validated under load (10+ simultaneous users)
- [ ] Error handling covers network failures and conflicts
- [ ] **Gemini Pro audit passed**: Architecture, performance, user experience
- [ ] **O3 audit passed**: CRDT implementation, conflict resolution, data integrity

**For sprint completion:**
- [ ] Real-time collaboration works reliably with 5+ users
- [ ] Visual-code bidirectional sync maintains consistency
- [ ] Performance targets met (sub-100ms sync, 60fps interactions)
- [ ] Offline editing with successful recovery demonstrated
- [ ] Comprehensive telemetry provides actionable insights

---

## Quality Gates & Audit Requirements

### Collaboration-Specific Testing
- [ ] Multi-user stress testing with simulated network conditions
- [ ] Conflict resolution testing with adversarial scenarios
- [ ] Performance testing with large experiments and many users
- [ ] Offline-online transition testing
- [ ] Data consistency validation across all collaboration scenarios

---

## Risk Mitigation

**Technical Risks:**
- **CRDT complexity**: Use battle-tested Y.js library, comprehensive testing
- **Network reliability**: Implement robust reconnection and conflict resolution
- **Performance degradation**: Continuous monitoring and optimization

**User Experience Risks:**
- **Collaboration confusion**: Clear presence indicators and conflict resolution UI
- **Data loss fears**: Visible sync status and reliable offline support

---

*Previous: [Sprint 3: GUI View Layer](sprint3.md) | Next: [Sprint 5: Simulation & Intelligence](sprint5.md)*

